Problem Definition
Driving schools in Rwanda (and similar contexts) manage student registration, instructor scheduling, vehicle allocation, lesson tracking, and government exam scheduling largely through paper registers or basic spreadsheets. This causes double-booking of instructors/vehicles, lost payment records, and no way to track a student's progress toward their driving test eligibility.
Context of Use
A driving school with multiple instructors, a limited fleet of vehicles, and students enrolled in different license categories (motorcycle, light vehicle, heavy truck) needs a system to manage the full student lifecycle — from registration to theory/practical lessons to final exam scheduling.
Target Users

School administrators (register students, manage payments, generate reports)
Instructors (view their schedule, log completed lessons)
Management (view revenue, vehicle utilization, pass rates via dashboards)

Project Objectives

Digitize student registration and package/category enrollment
Automate instructor and vehicle scheduling, preventing double-booking
Track lesson attendance and progress toward exam eligibility
Track payments and outstanding balances per student
Enforce business rules (e.g., no transactions on weekdays/holidays) with full audit logging
Provide analytics on revenue, pass rates, and instructor performance

Expected Benefits

Reduced scheduling conflicts
Accurate financial tracking
Data-driven decisions on vehicle/instructor allocation
Full audit trail for accountability
